# ADS-B Flight Tracker                                                                               
                                                                                          
  I have a Raspberry Pi running as a FlightRadar24 feeder — it has an SDR antenna attached that        
  receives ADS-B signals from aircraft flying overhead and uploads them to FlightRadar24. I wanted to  
  also use that data myself, so I built this: a real-time flight tracker that pulls the decoded        
  aircraft data off the Pi and displays it on a live map hosted online.                                
                  
  ## How it works

  The Pi runs `dump1090-mutability` which decodes the raw ADS-B radio signals and writes the aircraft
  data (position, altitude, speed, heading, squawk, etc.) to a JSON file at
  `/run/dump1090-mutability/aircraft.json` every few seconds. A bash script on the Pi reads that file
  and POSTs it to a Node.js backend hosted on Railway. The backend broadcasts the data to any connected
   browsers via WebSocket, and the frontend plots the planes on a Leaflet.js map in real time.

  ## Stack

  - **Pi side:** bash script + systemd service
  - **Backend:** Node.js, Express, ws — hosted on Railway
  - **Frontend:** Leaflet.js, plain HTML/JS — served by the backend

  ---

  ## Setting this up yourself

  ### Prerequisites

  - Raspberry Pi running FlightRadar24 OS (or any OS running `dump1090` or `dump1090-mutability`)
  - `dump1090-mutability` must be running with the `--write-json` flag pointing to a directory
  - A Railway account for hosting the backend

  ### 1. Verify dump1090 is writing data

  SSH into your Pi and check:

  ```bash
  ls /run/dump1090-mutability/
  cat /run/dump1090-mutability/aircraft.json

  You should see a JSON file with an aircraft array. If the array is empty, no planes are currently in
  range — that's fine, the file should still exist.

  If the directory doesn't exist, check that dump1090-mutability is running:

  ps aux | grep dump1090

  2. Set up the Pi forwarder

  Create the script:

  sudo mkdir -p /opt/adsb-forwarder
  sudo nano /opt/adsb-forwarder/forwarder.sh

  Paste this in:

  #!/bin/bash
  AIRCRAFT_FILE="/run/dump1090-mutability/aircraft.json"
  CLOUD_ENDPOINT="https://your-backend.railway.app/api/aircraft"
  API_KEY="your-secret-key"

  while true; do
      if [ -f "$AIRCRAFT_FILE" ]; then
          payload=$(cat "$AIRCRAFT_FILE")
          if [ -n "$payload" ]; then
              curl --http1.1 -s -X POST "$CLOUD_ENDPOINT" \
                  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
                  -H "X-API-Key: $API_KEY" \
                  --data-raw "$payload" \
                  > /dev/null
          fi
      fi
      sleep 3
  done

  Make it executable:

  sudo chmod +x /opt/adsb-forwarder/forwarder.sh

  Register it as a systemd service so it runs on boot:

  sudo nano /etc/systemd/system/adsb-forwarder.service

  [Unit]
  Description=ADS-B Data Forwarder
  After=network.target

  [Service]
  ExecStart=/bin/bash /opt/adsb-forwarder/forwarder.sh
  Restart=always
  User=pi

  [Install]
  WantedBy=multi-user.target

  Enable and start it:

  sudo systemctl enable adsb-forwarder
  sudo systemctl start adsb-forwarder
  sudo systemctl status adsb-forwarder

  3. Deploy the backend to Railway

  Install dependencies and deploy:

  cd adsb-backend
  npm install

  Push the project to a GitHub repo, then in Railway:

  1. Create a new project → Deploy from GitHub repo
  2. Connect your repo
  3. Go to the service → Variables tab and add:
  API_KEY = your-secret-key
  4. Railway will auto-detect Node.js and deploy. Copy your Railway URL.

  4. Update the forwarder and frontend with your Railway URL

  Edit the forwarder script on the Pi:

  sudo nano /opt/adsb-forwarder/forwarder.sh

  Update CLOUD_ENDPOINT and API_KEY to match your Railway URL and the key you set.

  Restart the service:

  sudo systemctl restart adsb-forwarder

  In public/index.html, update the WebSocket URL and map center:

  const ws = new WebSocket(`wss://your-backend.railway.app`);
  // ...
  const map = L.map('map').setView([YOUR_LAT, YOUR_LON], 8);

  5. Test the pipeline

  From the Pi, send a test aircraft to verify everything is connected:

  curl --http1.1 -X POST https://your-backend.railway.app/api/aircraft -H "Content-Type:
  application/json" -H "X-API-Key: your-secret-key" -d '{"aircraft":[{"hex":"test01","lat":42.787,"lon"
  :-71.332,"altitude":20000,"speed":350,"track":280,"squawk":"1200"}]}'

  You should get {"ok":true,"count":1} back and see a plane appear on the map.

  ---
  Where the API key lives

  The API key is the only secret in this project. It just prevents random people from POSTing junk data
   to your endpoint. It needs to match in two places:

  - Railway → Variables tab → API_KEY
  - Pi → /opt/adsb-forwarder/forwarder.sh → API_KEY=

  ---
  Notes

  - aircraft.json is updated by dump1090 roughly every second; the forwarder POSTs every 3 seconds
  - Aircraft without a known position (no lat/lon yet) are included in the raw file but won't appear on
   the map since Leaflet needs coordinates
  - The history_*.json files in /run/dump1090-mutability/ are a rolling 120-entry position history
  buffer maintained by dump1090 — not used by this project but useful if you want to draw flight trails
  - dump978-fr24 also runs on FR24 OS — that handles UAT (978 MHz) used by smaller GA aircraft in the
  US. This project only uses the 1090 MHz ADS-B data from dump1090